{
  "text": "Vette 5 characterized by a complex interaction of central and peripheral information [CITATION_1] . Most recently, multi-directional surface perturbations were used to show that muscle synergies represent a general neural control strategy [CITATION_2] , but that such a global control pattern cannot be applied to all postural tasks [CITATION_3] . Besides the surface perturbations, postural perturbations have also been applied directly to the trunk in order to quantify human trunk stiffness [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and postural reflex properties [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] or to determine the effect of external loads on lumbar spine stability [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] , muscle activation patterns [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] , and body kinematics [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] . Similarly, subjects have been perturbed to characterize protective stepping responses in young and older adults [CITATION_19] [CITATION_20] or to study falls in the anterior direction after perturbation of a forward leaning posture [CITATION_21] [CITATION_22] .",
